name: Window
comment:
Top-level container for the current browser tab or window.

In a web browser, each window has a dart-dom-html.Window object, but within the context of a script, this object represents only the current window. Each other window, tab, and iframe has its own dart-dom-html.Window object.

Each window contains a dart-dom-html.Document object, which contains all of the window's content.

Use the top-level window object to access the current window. For example:

// Draw a scene when the window repaints.
drawScene(num delta) {...}
window.animationFrame.then(drawScene);.

// Write to the console.
window.console.log('Jinkies!');
window.console.error('Jeepers!');

Note: This class represents only the current window, while dart-dom-html.WindowBase is a representation of any window, including other tabs, windows, and frames.

See also

  • dart-dom-html.WindowBase

Other resources

  • DOM Window from MDN.
  • Window from the W3C.

animationFrame.name: animationFrame
animationFrame.comment:
Returns a Future that completes just before the window is about to repaint so the user can draw an animation frame.

If you need to later cancel this animation, use dart-dom-html.Window.requestAnimationFrame instead.

The dart-async.Future completes to a timestamp that represents a floating point value of the number of milliseconds that have elapsed since the page started to load (which is also the timestamp at this call to animationFrame).

Note: The code that runs when the future completes should call dart-dom-html.Window.animationFrame again for the animation to continue.

parent.name: parent
parent.comment:
A reference to the parent of this window.

If this dart-dom-html.WindowBase has no parent, dart-dom-html.Window.parent will return a reference to the dart-dom-html.WindowBase itself.

IFrameElement myIFrame = new IFrameElement();
window.document.body.elements.add(myIFrame);
print(myIframe.contentWindow.parent == window) // 'true'

print(window.parent == window) // 'true'

top.name: top
top.comment:
A reference to the topmost window in the window hierarchy.

If this dart-dom-html.WindowBase is the topmost dart-dom-html.WindowBase, dart-dom-html.Window.top will return a reference to the dart-dom-html.WindowBase itself.

// Add an IFrame to the current window.
IFrameElement myIFrame = new IFrameElement();
window.document.body.elements.add(myIFrame);

// Add an IFrame inside of the other IFrame.
IFrameElement innerIFrame = new IFrameElement();
myIFrame.elements.add(innerIFrame);

print(myIframe.contentWindow.top == window) // 'true'
print(innerIFrame.contentWindow.top == window) // 'true'

print(window.top == window) // 'true'

requestAnimationFrame.name: requestAnimationFrame
requestAnimationFrame.comment:
Called to draw an animation frame and then request the window to repaint after dart-dom-html.Window.requestAnimationFrame.callback has finished (creating the animation).

Use this method only if you need to later call dart-dom-html.Window.cancelAnimationFrame. If not, the preferred Dart idiom is to set animation frames by calling dart-dom-html.Window.animationFrame, which returns a Future.

Returns a non-zero valued integer to represent the request id for this request. This value only needs to be saved if you intend to call dart-dom-html.Window.cancelAnimationFrame so you can specify the particular animation to cancel.

Note: The supplied dart-dom-html.Window.requestAnimationFrame.callback needs to call dart-dom-html.Window.requestAnimationFrame again for the animation to continue.

Because the file system is sandboxed, applications cannot access file systems created in other web pages.

close.name: close
close.comment:
Closes the window.

This method should only succeed if the dart-dom-html.WindowBase object is script-closeable and the window calling dart-dom-html.Window.close is allowed to navigate the window.

A window is script-closeable if it is either a window that was opened by another window, or if it is a window with only one document in its history.

A window might not be allowed to navigate, and therefore close, another window due to browser security features.

var other = window.open('http://www.example.com', 'foo');
// Closes other window, as it is script-closeable.
other.close();
print(other.closed()); // 'true'

window.location('http://www.mysite.com', 'foo');
// Does not close this window, as the history has changed.
window.close();
print(window.closed()); // 'false'

See also:

  • Window close discussion from the W3C

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-dom-html.Window.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-dom-html.Window.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-dom-html.Window.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-dom-html.Window.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-dom-html.Window.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-dom-html.Window.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-dom-html.Window.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

close.name: close
close.comment:
Closes the window.

This method should only succeed if the dart-dom-html.WindowBase object is script-closeable and the window calling dart-dom-html.Window.close is allowed to navigate the window.

A window is script-closeable if it is either a window that was opened by another window, or if it is a window with only one document in its history.

A window might not be allowed to navigate, and therefore close, another window due to browser security features.

var other = window.open('http://www.example.com', 'foo');
// Closes other window, as it is script-closeable.
other.close();
print(other.closed()); // 'true'

window.location('http://www.mysite.com', 'foo');
